   </info>
   <refnamediv>
       <refname>lagbounds</refname>
               <refpurpose>lag bounds in a regression </refpurpose>
   </refnamediv>
 
        <refsynopsisdiv>
               <title>CALLING SEQUENCE</title>
               <synopsis>[bounds_out]=lagbounds(bounds_in,l)</synopsis>
        </refsynopsisdiv>
 
        <refsection>
           <title>PARAMETERS</title>
           <variablelist>
           <varlistentry>
 
           <term>Input</term>
 
<listitem><para>*  <term> bounds_in </term> =    the original bounds</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>*  <term> l </term> =    the lag (positive or negative, if you want to extend bounds in the past)</para></listitem>
 
 
 
<listitem><para>&#160;</para></listitem>
 
           </varlistentry>
 
          <varlistentry>
 
          <term>Output</term>
 
<listitem><para>*  <term> bounds_out </term> =    the lagged bounds</para></listitem>
 
 
          </varlistentry>
          </variablelist>
        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>DESCRIPTION</title>
Cuts the bounds at the start of the period. If the lag is negative, then bounds are extended in the past for a number of peridos equal
to the absolute value of the lag.
<para> </para>

        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>EXAMPLE</title>
              <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
lagbounds(['1985q2';'1997q4'],3)// Provides the (2x1) vector:
// ['1986q1'
// '1997q4']
 
grocer_boundsvar=lagbounds(grocer_boundsvarb,-grocer_l-1)// taken from function cadf
               ]]></programlisting>
        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
